{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477143"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:57:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:57:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14182"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14182"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.5,0.07,0.23,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6865"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111047"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6865","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6865"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14182"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93167"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1074"},{"type":"tags","id":"2355"},{"type":"tags","id":"2998"},{"type":"tags","id":"3557"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"},{"type":"tags","id":"12936"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15638"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18050"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40163"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45118"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111047"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-day-old boy is reviewed in the Special Care nursery with his parents in attendance due to noticeable and persistent tremors. He was born at term via spontaneous vaginal delivery with no immediate complications. His birth weight was 3.2 kg. He is exclusively breastfed and has been feeding well. His mother has a history of opioid use disorder but reports being on a methadone maintenance program throughout pregnancy. She denies using any illicit substances during pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the neonate appears well-nourished but is irritable and jittery. His pulse rate is 140/min, respiratory rate 50/min, temperature 36.8\u00b0C, and capillary refill time is 2 seconds. The jitteriness stops when the limbs are held but resumes upon release. There are no dysmorphic features or other abnormal findings on examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perform lumbar puncture","Measure blood glucose","Start phenobarbital","Obtain urine toxicology screen","Administer naloxone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a neonate with jitteriness, which can be a sign of various conditions including neonatal abstinence syndrome (NAS) and hypoglycaemia. Given the maternal history of opioid use disorder and methadone maintenance, NAS is a strong possibility. However, hypoglycaemia is also a common cause of neonatal jitteriness and can occur in any newborn, regardless of maternal history.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management is to \u003Cstrong\u003Emeasure blood glucose\u003C/strong\u003E. This is a quick, minimally invasive test that can immediately identify or rule out hypoglycaemia, which is a potentially dangerous condition requiring prompt treatment. If hypoglycaemia is present, it needs to be corrected before pursuing other diagnoses or treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering naloxone\u003C/strong\u003E would be contraindicated in this situation. Even if NAS is suspected, naloxone can precipitate acute withdrawal in opioid-exposed neonates, potentially leading to seizures and other severe symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerforming a lumbar puncture\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at this stage. While central nervous system infections can cause jitteriness, there are no signs of sepsis or specific indications for a lumbar puncture in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStarting phenobarbital\u003C/strong\u003E is premature at this point. While phenobarbital is sometimes used in the treatment of NAS, it\u0027s not the first-line management, especially before a definitive diagnosis is made and other causes of jitteriness are ruled out.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObtaining a urine toxicology screen\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful in the overall management, particularly if NAS is suspected. However, it\u0027s not the most urgent next step and wouldn\u0027t provide immediate actionable information like a blood glucose measurement would.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter checking the blood glucose, if it\u0027s normal, the next steps would involve a more comprehensive evaluation for NAS using a standardised scoring system (e.g., Finnegan score), and potentially initiating supportive care or pharmacological treatment if indicated. Continuous monitoring and reassessment would be crucial in managing this neonate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Jitteriness in neonates can be a sign of neonatal abstinence syndrome or hypoglycaemia.","A thorough maternal history is crucial in evaluating neonatal jitteriness.","Blood glucose measurement is an essential initial investigation in a jittery neonate."],"references":["Rosman NP, Donnelly JH, Braun MA. The jittery newborn and infant: a review. J Dev Behav Pediatr. 1984 Oct;5(5):263-73. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/6149233/","Shuper A, Zalzberg J, Weitz R, Mimouni M. Jitteriness beyond the neonatal period: a benign pattern of movement in infancy. J Child Neurol. 1991 Jul;6(3):243-5. Available at: https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/10.1177/088307389100600307","Rosenfeld E, Thornton PS. Hypoglycemia in Neonates, Infants, and Children. [Updated 2023 Aug 22]. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc.; 2000-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK594592/","Neonatal abstinence syndrome (NAS). In: The Royal Women\u2019s Hospital Clinical Guidelines [online]. Accessed 2025 Jun 25. Available at: https://thewomens.r.worldssl.net/images/uploads/downloadable-records/clinical-guidelines/drug-and-alcohol-neonatal-abstinence-syndrome-nas_280720.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93167"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14182"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93167","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93167"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-07T16:39:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-07T16:40:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6865"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111047"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}}